`crates/ctx-scan/src` is the standalone, git-independent driver that walks an arbitrary directory, decides what's stale by content hash, and drives `ctx-summarize` to (re)generate `.context/` leaf and rollup summaries — plus the CLI/binary that exposes this as `ctx-scan` and a Claude Code Stop-hook integration. Depending on this crate gets you three programmatic entry points (`runner::scan_run`, `check_run`, `update_run`) plus a `dispatch`-based CLI; internally, work flows walker → hash → runner → (summarize via ctx-summarize) → hash::store/readme.

The core cross-file contract: `--check` must never call the model (pure hash diff) and `--update` must regenerate only what changed — this invariant spans `hash.rs` (computes/diffs the Merkle tree, sorts `stale_dirs` deepest-first) and `runner.rs` (`regenerate` relies on that ordering to process changed leaves, then orphans, then stale rollups bottom-up so parents see fresh children). `walker.rs` and `hash.rs` both consume `ctx_summarize::fs`/`cpath` conventions and must stay in sync with ctx-summarize's own path/scope logic — `.ctxignore` scope (seeded once from `.gitignore`) is shared via `fs::scope_matcher`, and sidecar layout is shared via `cpath::context_dir_of`/`ancestor_dirs`.

Prompt resolution is a repeated, deliberate quirk: `cli.rs` and `runner.rs` both resolve `prompts_dir`/`prompts` against the process cwd, never the scanned `base` — CTX's prompts live outside the target tree, and this must hold in any new entry point. `cli.rs` also encodes the `--approve` blast-radius gate whose actual enforcement (`MAX_TARGETS`) lives in `runner.rs`'s `scope_check`; the two must stay numerically in sync (`cli.rs`'s `stop_hook` message pre-hints the same threshold). `main.rs` guarantees stop-hook mode always exits 0 regardless of internal error, matching `cli::stop_hook`'s fail-open contract.

Each child's role here: `walker.rs` produces the scoped file list; `hash.rs` turns it into a change-detection tree and diff; `runner.rs` is the sole orchestrator tying walker+hash+ctx-summarize+readme together; `cli.rs`/`main.rs` are argv-to-orchestrator glue; `readme.rs` writes the static human-facing `.context/README.md`; `error.rs` unifies error types crate-wide via `#[from]` conversions from `ctx_summarize::SummError`.

No `intent.md` exists for this directory.